following best describes the interpretation and management of hepatitis A virus serology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive IgM indicates past infection","Positive IgM indicates acute infection","Positive IgM indicates successful vaccination","Positive IgG requires antiviral therapy","Positive IgG requires immunoglobulin therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe interpretation of hepatitis A serology is important for diagnosis and management:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive IgM indicates past infection\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - IgM antibodies indicate acute or recent infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive IgM indicates acute infection\u003C/strong\u003E is correct - IgM appears early and indicates current or recent infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive IgM indicates successful vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - vaccination induces only IgG antibodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive IgG requires antiviral therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - hepatitis A is self-limiting and requires only supportive care\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive IgG requires immunoglobulin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - immunoglobulin may be used for post-exposure prophylaxis but is not a treatment\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis A virus IgG appears later in the course of infection and persists indefinitely, indicating either past infection or vaccination. The disease is typically self-limiting and resolves without specific treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatitis A virus IgM indicates acute or recent infection while IgG indicates past infection or vaccination","Hepatitis A is typically self-limiting and requires only supportive care","Serological testing helps distinguish between acute infection, past infection, and vaccination status"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53990"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15356"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53990"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:12:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:13:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8047"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68533"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}}